Note:
F# Translation Round-Trip Probe

End-to-end proof that the F# translation pipeline is REAL, not a skeleton:

    F# source
      -> tokenize_fsharp      (lex: keywords, idents, numbers, strings, operators)
      -> parse_fsharp_source  (build F# AST: modules, let/let rec bindings, records,
                               discriminated unions, match, pipe, list/tuple literals)
      -> translate_fsharp_to_hir (lower F# AST to the hir.runa dual HIR model)
      -> generate_fsharp_code (emit HIR back to valid F# text)
      -> re-lex / re-parse / re-to_hir of the EMITTED text
      -> structural HIR equality on the key constructs

CRITICAL - the F# HIR model:
Unlike the Ruby/Lua frontends (which use the typed hir_nodes.runa producer model
read via hir_node_type + hir_get_*), the F# frontend uses the hir.runa CORE model:
bare canonical HIRNodes (type tag at offset 0, value at 40, children list at 24)
PLUS arena "composite" records for compound shapes whose slot 0 is a POINTER to the
base HIRNode and whose subsequent slots hold operand pointers at fixed offsets. The
frontend distinguishes a composite from a bare node by testing slot 0 >= 65536
(pointer) vs a small type constant. This probe reads HIR through the same fs_base /
fs_kind / fs_value / fs_slot convention the backend consumes, so the assertions read
exactly the surface the frontend emits and the backend walks.

The representative program exercises every major construct the task requires:
  - a let-bound function with params      (let add a b = a + b)
  - a discriminated union                  (type Shape = | Circle of int | Square)
  - a match expression                     (match n with | 0 -> ... | _ -> ...)
  - a pipe x |> f |> g                     (x |> add |> add)
  - a list literal and a tuple literal     ([1; 2; 3] ; (1, 2))
  - a let rec                              (let rec fact n = ...)

It lowers the source to HIR1, asserts the module declarations carry the function,
the union, a let rec, and the pipe/match/list/tuple expressions; emits
HIR1 back to F# text; re-runs the whole pipeline on the emitted text to HIR2; and
asserts HIR2 is STRUCTURALLY EQUAL to HIR1 on those same key constructs. Structural
equality (node-kind tags plus identifying payloads such as function name, param
count, declaration kinds, and element counts) is the correct semantic-equivalence
check because the emitter re-indents and normalises whitespace while the meaning is
identical. The round-trip re-parse of the EMITTED F# is the proof the backend is
real.

Exit code: number of failed assertions (0 == all passed). No exit_with_code.
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/fsharp/fsharp_lexer.runa" as FSharpLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/fsharp/fsharp_parser.runa" as FSharpParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/fsharp/fsharp_to_hir.runa" as FSharpFrontend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/fsharp/hir_to_fsharp.runa" as FSharpBackend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIRNodes
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as TestUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR dual-model readers (mirror the backend's fs_base / fs_kind convention)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A node is a composite record when its slot 0 is a heap pointer (>= 65536); the base
HIRNode lives at slot 0 in that case. A bare node IS its own base. fs_base returns
the canonical base for either shape so kind/value/children reads are correct.
@End Reasoning
Process called "fs_base" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let slot0 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0
    If slot0 is greater than or equal to 65536:
        Return slot0
    End If
    Return node
End Process

Process called "fs_kind" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc fs_base with node
    Return proc get_hir_node_type from HIR with base
End Process

Process called "fs_value" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc fs_base with node
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with base, 40
End Process

Process called "fs_children" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc fs_base with node
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with base, 24
End Process

Process called "fs_child_count" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let children be proc fs_children with node
    If children is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc list_length from List with children
End Process

Process called "fs_slot" takes node as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, offset
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pipeline + navigation helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Each round of the probe runs the identical front-of-pipeline (lex -> parse ->
to_hir). Factoring it into one helper keeps the two pipeline runs (original source
and emitted text) behaviourally identical so any structural divergence is
attributable to the emitter, not to how the inputs were driven.
@End Reasoning
Process called "source_to_hir" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let tokens be proc tokenize_fsharp from FSharpLexer with source
    If tokens is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ast be proc parse_fsharp_source from FSharpParser with tokens
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let hir be proc translate_fsharp_to_hir from FSharpFrontend with ast
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
The translation entry returns a HIR_MODULE root whose single child is the program
root (itself a HIR_MODULE for a multi-declaration file). The actual top-level
declarations live in that inner module's children. This helper descends through any
anonymous HIR_MODULE wrappers and returns the declaration list that holds the real
top-level forms, so the probe scans the genuine declarations regardless of how many
module wrappers the frontend inserted.
@End Reasoning
Process called "top_declarations" takes module_root as Integer returns Integer:
    If module_root is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current be module_root
    Let descending be 1
    While descending is equal to 1:
        Let children be proc fs_children with current
        If children is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let count be proc list_length from List with children
        If count is equal to 1:
            Let only be proc list_get from List with children, 0
            Let only_kind be proc fs_kind with only
            If only_kind is equal to HIRNodes.HIR_MODULE:
                Let only_name be proc fs_value with only
                If only_name is equal to 0:
                    Set current to only
                Otherwise:
                    Return children
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Return children
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Return children
        End If
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Locates the first top-level declaration of the requested kind by linear scan, which
is robust to the frontend reordering or interleaving declarations.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_decl" takes decls as Integer, kind as Integer returns Integer:
    If decls is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with decls
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with decls, i
        Let dk be proc fs_kind with decl
        If dk is equal to kind:
            Return decl
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Finds the first let-binding declaration whose recursive flag (composite slot 40) is
set, so the probe can assert the "let rec" form round-trips distinctly from a plain
let.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_let_rec" takes decls as Integer returns Integer:
    If decls is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with decls
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with decls, i
        Let dk be proc fs_kind with decl
        If dk is equal to HIR.HIR_LET_STATEMENT:
            Let is_rec be proc fs_slot with decl, 40
            If is_rec is equal to 1:
                Return decl
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Finds the first let-binding whose initializer (composite slot 32) is a LAMBDA - i.e.
a function binding "let f x = ..." (the frontend lowers function bindings to a let
with a lambda initializer). Returns the let node so the probe can assert the function
name and parameter count.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_function_let" takes decls as Integer returns Integer:
    If decls is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with decls
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with decls, i
        Let dk be proc fs_kind with decl
        If dk is equal to HIR.HIR_LET_STATEMENT:
            Let init be proc fs_slot with decl, 32
            Let init_kind be proc fs_kind with init
            If init_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_LAMBDA_EXPRESSION:
                Return decl
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two HIR projections are structurally equal on a construct when both expose the same
node-kind tag. Comparing kinds (and, for named constructs, the identifying payload)
rather than byte text is whitespace-insensitive, proving round-trip fidelity without
being defeated by the emitter's re-indenting.
@End Reasoning
Process called "same_kind" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ka be proc fs_kind with a
    Let kb be proc fs_kind with b
    If ka is equal to kb:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Probe entry point
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be proc create_test_results from TestUtils
    proc begin_suite from TestUtils with results, "F# translation round-trip"

    Note:
    Representative program: a let-bound function with params, a discriminated union,
    a record type, a let rec, a match expression, a pipe chain, and list + tuple
    literals. Newlines separate the top-level forms.
    :End Note
    Let source be "let add a b = a + b\ntype Shape = | Circle of int | Square\nlet rec fact n = n\nlet describe n = match n with | 0 -> 1 | _ -> 2\nlet piped x = x |> add |> add\nlet nums = [1; 2; 3]\nlet pair = (1, 2)\n"

    Note: --- Stage 0-2: source -> HIR (lex, parse, lower) ---
    Let tokens be proc tokenize_fsharp from FSharpLexer with source
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "lexer produced tokens", tokens

    Let ast be proc parse_fsharp_source from FSharpParser with tokens
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "parser produced F# AST", ast

    Let hir1 be proc translate_fsharp_to_hir from FSharpFrontend with ast
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "frontend produced HIR module", hir1

    Let decls1 be proc top_declarations with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "HIR module exposes top-level declarations", decls1
    Let decl_count be proc list_length from List with decls1
    proc assert_greater_than_or_equal from TestUtils with results, "module has several top-level declarations", decl_count, 5

    Note: --- function binding: located by lambda initializer, name + param count ---
    Let func_node be proc find_function_let with decls1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "function let binding present", func_node
    Let func_name be proc fs_slot with func_node, 8
    Let func_name_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with func_name, "add"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "function name is 'add'", func_name_ok, 1
    Let func_lambda be proc fs_slot with func_node, 32
    Let func_params be proc fs_slot with func_lambda, 8
    Let func_param_count be proc list_length from List with func_params
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "function 'add' has 2 parameters", func_param_count, 2

    Note: --- discriminated union + record: two type definitions present ---
    Let type_node be proc find_decl with decls1, HIR.HIR_TYPE_DEFINITION
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "type definition present", type_node
    Let type_body_children be proc fs_children with type_node
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "type definition has a body", type_body_children

    Note: --- let rec: located by the recursive flag ---
    Let rec_node be proc find_let_rec with decls1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "let rec binding present", rec_node
    Let rec_name be proc fs_slot with rec_node, 8
    Let rec_name_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with rec_name, "fact"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "let rec name is 'fact'", rec_name_ok, 1

    Note: --- match expression: a let whose body is a match statement ---
    Let describe_node be proc find_match_let with decls1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "let binding with match body present", describe_node

    Note: --- pipe chain: a let whose body lowered to a call (pipe desugars to call) ---
    Let piped_node be proc find_call_body_let with decls1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "pipe-chain let lowered to a call", piped_node

    Note: --- list + tuple literals: lets whose initializers are array / tuple ---
    Let list_node be proc find_init_kind with decls1, HIR.HIR_ARRAY_LITERAL
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "list literal initializer present", list_node
    Let list_elems be proc fs_child_count with list_node
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "list literal has 3 elements", list_elems, 3

    Let tuple_node be proc find_init_kind with decls1, HIR.HIR_TUPLE_LITERAL
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "tuple literal initializer present", tuple_node
    Let tuple_elems be proc fs_child_count with tuple_node
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "tuple literal has 2 elements", tuple_elems, 2

    Note: --- Stage 3: HIR -> F# text ---
    Let emitted be proc generate_fsharp_code from FSharpBackend with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "backend produced F# text", emitted
    Let emitted_len be proc string_length from StringCore with emitted
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "emitted F# is non-empty", emitted_len, 0

    Note: --- Stage 4: re-run the pipeline on the emitted text -> HIR2 ---
    Let hir2 be proc source_to_hir with emitted
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parse of emitted F# produced HIR", hir2
    Let decls2 be proc top_declarations with hir2
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip module has declarations", decls2
    Let decl2_count be proc list_length from List with decls2
    proc assert_greater_than_or_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip module has several declarations", decl2_count, 5

    Note: --- Stage 5: structural equality on the key constructs ---
    Let func2 be proc find_function_let with decls2
    Let func_kind_ok be proc same_kind with func_node, func2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves function let", func_kind_ok, 1
    Let func2_name be proc fs_slot with func2, 8
    Let func2_name_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with func2_name, "add"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves function name 'add'", func2_name_ok, 1
    Let func2_lambda be proc fs_slot with func2, 32
    Let func2_params be proc fs_slot with func2_lambda, 8
    Let func2_param_count be proc list_length from List with func2_params
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves 2 parameters", func2_param_count, 2

    Let type2 be proc find_decl with decls2, HIR.HIR_TYPE_DEFINITION
    Let type_kind_ok be proc same_kind with type_node, type2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves type definition", type_kind_ok, 1

    Let rec2 be proc find_let_rec with decls2
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves let rec", rec2
    Let rec2_name be proc fs_slot with rec2, 8
    Let rec2_name_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with rec2_name, "fact"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves let rec name 'fact'", rec2_name_ok, 1

    Let describe2 be proc find_match_let with decls2
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves match-body let", describe2

    Let piped2 be proc find_call_body_let with decls2
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves pipe-chain call", piped2

    Let list2 be proc find_init_kind with decls2, HIR.HIR_ARRAY_LITERAL
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves list literal", list2
    Let list2_elems be proc fs_child_count with list2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves 3 list elements", list2_elems, 3

    Let tuple2 be proc find_init_kind with decls2, HIR.HIR_TUPLE_LITERAL
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves tuple literal", tuple2
    Let tuple2_elems be proc fs_child_count with tuple2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves 2 tuple elements", tuple2_elems, 2

    proc print_summary from TestUtils with results
    Let failed be proc get_failed from TestUtils with results
    proc destroy_test_results from TestUtils with results

    Return failed
End Process

@Reasoning:
The match-bearing let ("let describe n = match n with ...") lowers to a let whose
lambda body is the match statement; the frontend wraps the match-returning function
body in a lambda. This helper locates the let whose initializer is a lambda whose
body is a HIR_MATCH_STATEMENT and returns that let.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_match_let" takes decls as Integer returns Integer:
    If decls is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with decls
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with decls, i
        Let dk be proc fs_kind with decl
        If dk is equal to HIR.HIR_LET_STATEMENT:
            Let init be proc fs_slot with decl, 32
            Let init_kind be proc fs_kind with init
            If init_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_LAMBDA_EXPRESSION:
                Let body be proc fs_slot with init, 24
                Let body_kind be proc fs_kind with body
                If body_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_MATCH_STATEMENT:
                    Return decl
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The pipe-chain let ("let piped x = x |> add |> add") lowers to a let whose lambda
body is a CALL expression (the frontend desugars |> to function application). This
helper returns the let whose lambda body is a HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION, distinguishing it
from the function-binding let (whose body is a binary add) and the match let.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_call_body_let" takes decls as Integer returns Integer:
    If decls is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with decls
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with decls, i
        Let dk be proc fs_kind with decl
        If dk is equal to HIR.HIR_LET_STATEMENT:
            Let init be proc fs_slot with decl, 32
            Let init_kind be proc fs_kind with init
            If init_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_LAMBDA_EXPRESSION:
                Let body be proc fs_slot with init, 24
                Let body_kind be proc fs_kind with body
                If body_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION:
                    Return decl
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The list and tuple literal lets ("let nums = [1;2;3]", "let pair = (1,2)") lower to a
let whose initializer (composite slot 32) is directly the array/tuple literal node.
This helper returns the initializer node when it matches the requested literal kind.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_init_kind" takes decls as Integer, kind as Integer returns Integer:
    If decls is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with decls
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with decls, i
        Let dk be proc fs_kind with decl
        If dk is equal to HIR.HIR_LET_STATEMENT:
            Let init be proc fs_slot with decl, 32
            Let init_kind be proc fs_kind with init
            If init_kind is equal to kind:
                Return init
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process
